1
00:00:04,309 --> 00:00:06,569
In the previous lessons,

2
00:00:06,570 --> 00:00:10,980
you learned how to use univariate and bivariate plots to visualize your data,

3
00:00:10,980 --> 00:00:13,040
one or two variables at a time.

4
00:00:13,039 --> 00:00:14,764
In most of these cases,

5
00:00:14,765 --> 00:00:16,929
you use position like in scatter plots,

6
00:00:16,929 --> 00:00:20,410
or length like in bar charts for encoding your variables.

7
00:00:20,410 --> 00:00:25,379
This is because our perception for values is most precise with these encodings.

8
00:00:25,379 --> 00:00:29,769
This presents an issue for when we want to move on to multi-variate plots,

9
00:00:29,769 --> 00:00:32,469
or plots of three, or more variables.

10
00:00:32,469 --> 00:00:34,734
There will be ambiguity in value,

11
00:00:34,734 --> 00:00:39,994
if we try to embed three positional dimensions into a flat, two-dimensional image.

12
00:00:39,994 --> 00:00:44,449
Take for example this point on the three-dimensional axes here.

13
00:00:44,450 --> 00:00:48,600
What does that point's value on x, y, and z?

14
00:00:48,600 --> 00:00:53,164
Due to perspective, there are multiple possible values it could take.

15
00:00:53,164 --> 00:00:56,554
We can resolve the ambiguity with additional markings,

16
00:00:56,554 --> 00:01:00,034
but this is unreasonable if we have lots of data.

17
00:01:00,034 --> 00:01:03,379
In this lesson, you will learn about encodings that can be

18
00:01:03,380 --> 00:01:06,575
used to create effective multi-variate plots.

19
00:01:06,575 --> 00:01:09,650
You will also see other techniques like fastening

20
00:01:09,650 --> 00:01:13,370
that can expand on bivariate plots to make them multivariate.

21
00:01:13,370 --> 00:01:18,640
You will also learn about additional techniques that will help you in your analysis.

